{"continue":{"rvcontinue":"20180912183520|859241440","continue":"||"},"warnings":{"main":{"*":"Subscribe to the mediawiki-api-announce mailing list at <https://lists.wikimedia.org/mailman/listinfo/mediawiki-api-announce> for notice of API deprecations and breaking changes. Use [[Special:ApiFeatureUsage]] to see usage of deprecated features by your application."},"revisions":{"*":"Because \"rvslots\" was not specified, a legacy format has been used for the output. This format is deprecated, and in the future the new format will always be used."}},"query":{"normalized":[{"from":"Ro_Khanna","to":"Ro Khanna"}],"pages":{"38318277":{"pageid":38318277,"ns":0,"title":"Ro Khanna","revisions":[{"timestamp":"2018-09-15T06:34:51Z","contentformat":"text/x-wiki","contentmodel":"wikitext","*":"{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name = Ro Khanna\n|image = Ro Khanna, official portrait, 115th Congress.jpg\n|state = [[California]]\n|district = {{ushr|CA|17|17th}}\n|term_start = January 3, 2017\n|term_end =\n|predecessor = [[Mike Honda]]\n|successor =\n|birth_name = Rohit Khanna\n|birth_date = {{birth date and age|1976|9|13}}\n|birth_place = [[Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]],<br>U.S.\n|death_date =\n|death_place =\n|party = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|relatives = [[Amarnath Vidyalankar]] (Grandfather)\n|education = [[University of Chicago]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br>[[Yale University]] ([[Juris Doctor|JD]])\n|website = {{url|khanna.house.gov|House website}}\n}}\n'''Rohit Khanna''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|r|o\u028a|_|\u02c8|k|\u0251\u02d0|n|\u0259}}; born September 13, 1976) is an American academic, lawyer, and politician serving as the [[United States Representative|U.S. Representative]] from [[California's 17th congressional district]], since 2017. A member of the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]], he defeated eight-term incumbent Democratic Representative [[Mike Honda]] in the general election on November 8, 2016, after first running for the same seat in 2014. Khanna also served as the Deputy Assistant Secretary in the [[United States Department of Commerce]] under [[President of the United States|President]] [[Barack Obama]] from August 8, 2009, to August 2011.\n\nKhanna only accepts donations from individuals and is one of only six members of the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. House of Representatives]], and ten total members of [[United States Congress|Congress]], who do not take campaign contributions from [[Political Action Committees]] (PACs) or corporations.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://cleanslatenow.org/2017/09/15/u-s-senate-senators-pac-fundraising-in-their-current-election-cycles/|title=U.S. Senate \u2014 Senators' PAC Fundraising in their current Election Cycles|date=2017-09-15|work=CleanSlateNow.org|access-date=2018-02-08|language=en-US}}</ref><ref name=\"politico.com1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/tipsheets/politico-influence/2017/07/12/khanna-starts-pac-free-caucus-221295|title=Khanna starts PAC-free caucus|author=|date=July 12, 2017|website=POLITICO|access-date=October 21, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sfchronicle.com/opinion/openforum/article/No-PAC-Act-offers-voters-hope-to-be-heard-11056365.php|title='No PAC Act' offers voters hope to be heard|author=|date=|website=SFChronicle.com|access-date=October 21, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"cleanslatenow1\">{{cite web|url=https://cleanslatenow.org/2016/12/20/pac-fundraising-totals-and-the-115th-congress-house-of-representatives/ |title=PAC Fundraising Totals and the 115th Congress \u2013 House of Representatives @ |publisher=Cleanslatenow.org |date= |accessdate=January 19, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nKhanna was born in 1976 in [[Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]].<ref name=about/> His parents are [[Punjabis|Punjabi]] immigrants to the [[United States]] from [[India]]. His father is a chemical engineer who graduated from the [[Indian Institute of Technology]] (IIT) and the [[University of Michigan]], and his mother is a former substitute school teacher.<ref name=about/><ref>{{cite news|title=Meet 'Ro' Khanna, 3 Other Indian-Americans Elected to US Congress|url=https://www.thequint.com/world/2016/11/09/indian-americans-krishnamoorthi-harris-jayapal-register-big-win-us-elections-hillary-clinton-donald-trump|work=The Quint|date=November 10, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Herhold|first1=Scott|title=Ro Khanna's family narrative rivals that of Mike Honda|url=http://www.eastbaytimes.com/2015/06/17/ro-khannas-family-narrative-rivals-that-of-mike-honda/|work=East Bay Times|date=June 17, 2015}}</ref> Khanna's maternal grandfather, [[Amarnath Vidyalankar]], was part of India's independence movement, working with [[Lala Lajpat Rai]], and spent years in jail in the pursuit of human rights and freedom.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://164.100.47.132/LssNew/biodata_1_12/1098.htm|title=Members Bioprofile|publisher=164.100.47.132|date=December 8, 1902|accessdate=July 16, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldcat.org/identities/lccn-n50-59159|title=Towards socialism: a compilation|publisher=Worldcat.org |date=July 26, 1974|accessdate=July 16, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/1999/99aug19/head6.htm|title=Elections '99|publisher=Tribuneindia.com|date=August 19, 1999|accessdate=July 16, 2013}}</ref> In a ''Boston Globe'' op-ed, Khanna and Representative [[John Lewis (civil rights leader)|John Lewis]] examined how Gandhi's movement was intertwined with the civil rights movement.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/opinion/2018/04/05/the-intertwined-freedom-movements-gandhi-and-martin-luther-king/BmVLzhgwgJZE1Oz4CWiF4M/story.html|title=The intertwined freedom movements of Gandhi and Martin Luther King Jr. - The Boston Globe|publisher=|accessdate=July 26, 2018}}</ref> Khanna received his B.A. degree in economics with honors from the [[University of Chicago]] in 1998, where he was a member of [[Phi Beta Kappa]].<ref name=about>{{cite web|url=http://www.rokhanna.com/about.php|title=Ro Khanna profile|publisher=RoKhanna.com|accessdate=January 27, 2013}}</ref><ref name=appointed/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=SMCB&p_theme=smcb&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=10064DF7CCFA7118&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|title=Young hopeful touts vision|first=Justin|last=Jouvenal|date=January 14, 2004|newspaper=[[San Mateo County Times]]|accessdate=April 4, 2013}} {{subscription required|date=April 2013}}</ref> He attended [[Yale Law School]], receiving his law degree in 2001. He specialized in [[intellectual property law]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=OKTB&p_theme=oktb&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=129F7E81C7C17170&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|title=Obama taps Fremont man for tech post|first=John|last=Boudreau|newspaper=[[Oakland Tribune]]|date=August 7, 2009|accessdate=January 27, 2013}} {{subscription required|date=January 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Early work in politics, law, and teaching==\nAs a student at the University of Chicago, Khanna worked for [[William D. Burns]] walking precincts during [[Barack Obama]]'s first campaign for the [[Illinois Senate]] in 1996.<ref>{{cite web|last=Green |first=Joshua |url=http://www.businessweek.com/articles/2013-04-04/ro-khanna-silicon-valleys-wannabe-obama|title=Ro Khanna, Silicon Valley's Wannabe Obama|publisher=Businessweek|accessdate=July 16, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Jaffe|first=Alexandra|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/ballot-box/house-races/310795-top-5-house-primaries-to-watch|title=Top 5 House primaries to watch|publisher=Thehill.com|accessdate=July 16, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Margarita Lacabe (posted)|url=http://sanleandrotalk.voxpublica.org/2013/08/26/ro-khanna-a-political-portrait|title=Ro Khanna: A Political Portrait|publisher=Sanleandrotalk.voxpublica.org|date=August 26, 2013|accessdate=May 21, 2014}}</ref> Khanna interned for [[Jack Quinn (lawyer)|Jack Quinn]] when Quinn served as the [[Chief of Staff to the Vice President of the United States|Chief of Staff]] for [[Vice President of the United States|Vice President]] [[Al Gore]].<ref name=mercury/>\n\nPresident Obama appointed Khanna to a role in the [[United States Department of Commerce]] in 2009.<ref name=appointed>{{cite news|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=SJ&s_site=mercurynews&p_multi=SJ&p_theme=realcities&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=12A03B612F11ED40&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|newspaper=[[San Jose Mercury News]]|date=August 8, 2009|page=1C|title=Obama Taps Fremont Man, Ro Khanna's Selection Heartens Indo-American Community|accessdate=April 5, 2013}} {{subscription required|date=April 2013}}</ref> In his role as deputy assistant secretary,<ref name=sfgate2013>{{cite news|last=Marinucci|first=Carla|url=http://blog.sfgate.com/nov05election/2013/01/21/honda-v-khanna-could-silicon-valley-be-ground-zero-for-2014-house-asian-american-battle-royale-video|title=Honda v. Khanna: Could Silicon Valley be ground zero for 2014 House Asian-American battle royale?|publisher=Blog.sfgate.com|accessdate=January 24, 2013}}</ref> Khanna led international trade missions<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/ro-khanna-to-lead-us-energy-trade-mission-to/505038|title=Ro Khanna to lead US energy trade mission to India|publisher=Indian Express|date=August 21, 2009|accessdate=January 24, 2013}}</ref> and worked to increase United States exports.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=CO&s_site=charlotte&p_multi=CO&p_theme=realcities&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=12FDB98300BEE330&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|newspaper=Charlotte Observer|date=May 21, 2010|page=8A|title=Government helping firms expand exports|accessdate=April 5, 2013}} {{subscription required|date=April 2013}}</ref> He was later appointed to the White House Business Council.<ref name=sfgate2013/> Khanna resigned from the Department of Commerce in August 2011 to join [[Wilson Sonsini Goodrich & Rosati]], a law firm located in [[Silicon Valley]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=CFAB&p_theme=cfab&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=139433ED517C3DF8&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|title=Ex-U.S. Commerce official from Bay Area believes government can help, not hinder economy|first=John|last=Boudreau|date=August 20, 2011|newspaper=[[The Argus (Fremont)|The Argus]]|accessdate=April 5, 2013}} {{subscription required|date=April 2013}}</ref> His pro bono legal activity includes work with the Mississippi Center for Justice on several contractor fraud cases on behalf of Hurricane Katrina victims and co-authoring an amicus brief to the United States Supreme Court in the Mt. Holly case to allow for race discrimination suits under the Fair Housing Act of 1968.<ref>{{cite web|first=Keith |last=Kamisugi |url=http://equaljusticesociety.org/2013/11/05/brief-filed-with-supreme-court-in-mt-holly-case-says-implicit-bias-a-major-cause-of-housing-discrimination|title=Brief Filed with Supreme Court in Mt. Holly Case Says Implicit Bias a Major Cause of Housing Discrimination|publisher=Equal Justice Society|date=November 5, 2013|access-date=February 16, 2016}}</ref><ref>http://www.omm.com/newsroom/news.aspx?news=1271{{dead link|date=November 2016}}</ref> As part of a pro bono legal team, Khanna filed an amicus brief on behalf of 13 of the country's leading social scientists in the Supreme Court case ''Fisher v. University of Texas at Austin''. That brief included research that provided a deeper understanding of how a diverse educational environment benefits students and cited studies showing that race-conscious admissions policies used by institutions like the University of Texas result in a more diverse student body.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mercurynews.com/2017/08/06/donald-trump-immigration-affirmative-action-raise-act/|title=How Trump could reshape the American Dream|author=|date=August 6, 2017|website=MercuryNews.com|access-date=October 21, 2017}}</ref><ref>http://www.scotusblog.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/08/11-345-respondent-amicus-SOP.pdf</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wsgr.com/WSGR/Display.aspx?SectionName=clients/081312-social-scientists-amicus-brief.htm|title=Social Scientists File Amicus Brief with U.S. Supreme Court in High-Profile Affirmative Action Case - Wilson Sonsini Goodrich & Rosati|author=|date=|website=www.WSGR.com|access-date=October 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\nKhanna teaches [[economics]] at [[Stanford University]] and law at the [[Santa Clara University School of Law]],<ref name=about/> and has taught American Jurisprudence at [[San Francisco State University]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.clubrunner.ca/portal/story/StoryDetail.aspx?accountid=3975&sid=293676&stid=|archive-url=https://archive.is/20140826011330/http://www.clubrunner.ca/portal/story/StoryDetail.aspx?accountid=3975&sid=293676&stid=|dead-url=yes|archive-date=August 26, 2014|title=The Website You are Trying to Access is not Currently Active|publisher=|access-date=November 12, 2016}}</ref> He wrote a book on American competitiveness in business, ''Entrepreneurial Nation: Why Manufacturing is Still Key to America's Future'', which was published in 2012.<ref name=sfgate2013/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/kensweet/2012/08/13/former-obama-official-says-manufacturing-should-be-a-national-security-issue|title=Former Obama Official Says Manufacturing Should be a National Security Issue|publisher=Forbes.com|date=August 13, 2012|accessdate=April 5, 2013|first=Ken|last=Sweet}}</ref> Governor [[Jerry Brown]] appointed Khanna to the California [[Workforce Investment Board]] in 2012.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sfgate.com/business/bottomline/article/Governor-staffs-up-job-investment-panel-3822807.php|title=Governor staffs up job investment panel|first=Andrew S.|last=Ross|newspaper=San Francisco Chronicle|date=August 29, 2012|accessdate=January 27, 2013}}</ref> Khanna served on the board of Planned Parenthood Mar Monte from 2006 until 2013 while on leave from the Obama Administration.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibabuzz.com/politics/2013/09/24/ca17-honda-and-khanna-on-abortion-choice/|title=CA17: Honda and Khanna on abortion choice - Political Blotter|author=|date=September 24, 2013|website=IBABuzz.com|access-date=October 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n\n===Committee assignments===\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Armed Services|Committee on Armed Services]]'''\n** [[United States House Armed Services Subcommittee on Readiness|Subcommittee on Readiness]]\n** [[United States House Armed Services Subcommittee on Strategic Forces|Subcommittee on Strategic Forces]]\n* '''[[United States House Committee on the Budget|Committee on the Budget]]'''\n\n===Technology and manufacturing jobs===\n[[Nancy Pelosi]] tapped Khanna to draft the Internet Bill of Rights in wake of [[Cambridge Analytica]]'s breach and [[Mark Zuckerberg]]'s testimony to Congress.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mercurynews.com/2018/04/21/rep-ro-khanna-tapped-by-pelosi-to-draft-internet-bill-of-rights/|title=Rep. Ro Khanna tapped by Pelosi to draft \u201cInternet Bill of Rights\u201d|date=April 21, 2018|publisher=|accessdate=July 26, 2018}}</ref><ref>http://www.newsweek.com/facebook-silicon-valley-regulation-891989</ref>\n\nKhanna's Valor Act passed both the House and the Senate and was signed by President Trump on November 21, 2017. The bill will make it easier for companies to offer veterans apprenticeships.<ref>{{cite web|last=Arrington |first=Jodey |url=https://www.tribtalk.org/2017/11/15/bipartisanship-inspired-by-our-nations-heroes/ |title=Bipartisanship inspired by our nation's heroes |publisher=Tribtalk.org |date=November 15, 2017 |accessdate=January 19, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2017/11/21/president-donald-j-trump-signs-hr-194-hr-1545-hr-1679-hr-3243-and-hr |title=President Donald J. Trump Signs H.R. 194, H.R. 1545, H.R. 1679, H.R. 3243 and H.R. 3949 into Law |publisher=Whitehouse.gov |date=November 21, 2017 |accessdate=January 19, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn Kara Swisher's Recode Decode podcast, Khanna laid out his vision for how Silicon Valley needs to give back to all Americans.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/podcast/rep-ro-khanna-silicon-valley-should-give-back-to-all/id1011668648?i=1000384462376&mt=2|title=Recode Decode, hosted by Kara Swisher by Recode on Apple Podcasts|website=Apple Podcasts}}</ref> Khanna has also been a longtime supporter of bringing advanced manufacturing jobs across America and has written a book on the topic, ''Entrepreneurial Nation: Why Manufacturing Is Still Key To America's Future''.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books/about/Entrepreneurial_Nation_Why_Manufacturing.html?id=mCk7EwgRU64C&hl=en Entrepreneurial Nation: Why Manufacturing is Still Key to America's Future] by Ro Khanna. Google Books.</ref>\n\nIn March 2017, Khanna traveled to Paintsville, Kentucky, also known as \"Silicon Holler\", along with a bipartisan delegation from Congress, to lend support to TechHire Eastern Kentucky, a program that trains Kentuckians in fields like computer technology and coding. Khanna expressed support for a broad technology apprenticeship program, which could help areas of the United States like Appalachia by giving blue collar Americans the skills they need to launch future careers in the technology sector.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/states/california/story/2017/02/silicon-valley-heading-to-appalachia-with-jobs-message-109845|title=Khanna headed to Appalachia to support program that trains young people for tech jobs|publisher=|accessdate=April 18, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"politico.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/tipsheets/morning-tech/2017/03/silicon-valley-sends-its-ambassador-to-appalachia-219339|title=Silicon Valley sends its ambassador to Appalachia|publisher=|accessdate=April 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.msnbc.com/morning-joe/watch/how-congress-connects-to-jobs-of-the-future-897486915555|title=How Congress connects to jobs of the future|publisher=|accessdate=April 18, 2017}}</ref> The press has dubbed Khanna the \"Ambassador of Silicon Valley.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mercurynews.com/2017/06/23/ro-khanna-wants-to-be-silicon-valleys-ambassador-to-middle-america/|title=Ro Khanna wants to be Silicon Valley's ambassador to Middle America|author=|date=June 23, 2017|website=mercurynews.com|accessdate=October 21, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"politico.com\"/>\n\nIn May 2017, Khanna stood up for the Appalachian Regional Commission and Manufacturing Externship Partnership, a Reagan-era policy, when Trump's proposed 2018 budget zeroed out its funding. Khanna called for quadrupling the program's budget.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lnpdVDvgq3E&feature=youtu.be|title=Trump's budget fails to address US innovation|first=|last=Rep. Ro Khanna|date=May 26, 2017|publisher=|accessdate=October 21, 2017|via=YouTube}}</ref>\n\nKhanna passed his first piece of legislation, as the lead Democrat, with Majority Leader [[Kevin McCarthy (California politician)|Kevin McCarthy]] to enable veterans to use GI funding for tech training programs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mercurynews.com/2017/08/10/new-federal-program-could-help-veterans-join-the-tech-industry/|title=New federal program could help veterans join the tech industry|author=|date=August 10, 2017|website=mercurynews.com|accessdate=October 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\nKhanna called on Silicon Valley executives and technology companies to do more all across the country to create tech jobs and diversify their recruiting efforts by making sure to recruit the next generation of tech workers from not just Ivy League institutions but also from state schools and historically black colleges and universities. In a ''Washington Post'' op-ed he authored, Khanna wrote, \"Tech companies must offer an aspirational vision of how all Americans, regardless of geography, can benefit from a tech-driven economy. This means making investments not just in California, Massachusetts, and New York, but also in start-ups and entrepreneurs in cities and rural communities across the nation.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/trump-beat-silicon-valley-at-its-own-game-now-it-must-prove-itself/2017/10/16/a0160c36-af96-11e7-a908-a3470754bbb9_story.html|title=Opinion - Trump beat Silicon Valley at its own game. Now it must prove itself.|author=|date=|website=Washington Post|accessdate=October 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2018, Khanna and Representative Tim Ryan led a tour of venture capitalists encouraging them to invest in middle America.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tribtoday.com/news/local-news/2018/02/ryan-wants-merging-of-valleys/|title=Ryan wants merging of valleys - News, Sports, Jobs - Tribune Chronicle|website=www.tribtoday.com|accessdate=July 26, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vindy.com/news/2018/feb/22/led-by-ryan-khanna-venture-capitalists-k/|title=Congressman Ryan leads venture capitalists on Rust Belt tour - vindy.com|website=www.vindy.com|accessdate=July 26, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/with-jobs-in-mind-ohio-democrat-takes-venture-capitalists-on-midwest-road-trip-1519396730|title=With Jobs in Mind, Ohio Democrat Takes Venture Capitalists on Midwest Road Trip|first=Natalie|last=Andrews|date=February 23, 2018|publisher=|accessdate=July 26, 2018|via=www.wsj.com}}</ref>\n\nKhanna has been described as an \"unconventional ambassador\" for the Democratic Party in bringing tech and innovation across America.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/politics/la-na-pol-tech-trump-country-20180506-story.html|title=This Silicon Valley congressman wants to sell his vision to Trump country. Here's why Democrats' future could hinge on it|first=Evan|last=Halper|website=latimes.com|accessdate=July 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Economics ===\nKhanna has called on his colleagues to adopt a more progressive economic platform.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sacbee.com/opinion/op-ed/article139206973.html|title=A progressive's prescription for the future - The Sacramento Bee|publisher=|access-date=April 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/posteverything/wp/2017/02/23/how-to-help-small-manufacturers-and-how-not-to/|title=Perspective - How to help small manufacturers (and how not to)|publisher=|accessdate=April 18, 2017}}</ref> He is an original co-sponsor of [[Senator Bernie Sanders]]'s bill to make college affordable to all.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mic.com/articles/173013/bernie-sanders-introduces-college-for-all-act-to-make-public-colleges-tuition-free#.jnzt4UpDR|title=Bernie Sanders introduces \"College for All Act\" to make public colleges tuition-free|publisher=|access-date=April 18, 2017}}</ref> He also has proposed $1 trillion expansion of the earned income tax credit (EITC),<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://basicincome.org/news/2017/10/united-states-congressman-ro-khanna-introduces-eitc-bill-garners-comparison-bi/|title=Congressman Ro Khanna introduces EITC bill, garners comparison to BI|first=Peter|last=Vandevanter|date=2 October 2017|website=basicincome.org/news/|accessdate=March 26, 2018}}</ref> financed by a financial transaction tax, to help working families across America.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wired.com/2017/03/silicon-valley-lawmakers-1-trillion-plan-save-trump-country/|title=A Silicon Valley Lawmaker's $1 Trillion Plan to Save Trump Country|first=Issie|last=Lapowsky|publisher=|access-date=April 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn the Budget Committee, Khanna pointed out that Trump was for a [[single payer]] healthcare system in 2000.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oVyrqe1rAiE&feature=youtu.be|title=Trump Previously Supported Free Healthcare - Make Him Support It Now|first=|last=Secular Talk|date=March 22, 2017|publisher=|access-date=April 18, 2017|via=YouTube}}</ref> He now supports a bill to provide \"Medicare for All\" in the House.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/policy-and-politics/2017/3/29/15056672/single-payer-democrats-medicare|title=With Trumpcare dead and Obama gone, progressives are putting Medicare for All back on the table|publisher=|access-date=April 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\nFred Hiatt, the editor of the Editorial Page of the ''Washington Post'', has suggested that Khanna is a thoughtful and new economic voice for the Democratic Party.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/how-democrats-can-be-progressive-without-being-irresponsible/2017/04/09/c8128cf6-1bb1-11e7-855e-4824bbb5d748_story.html|title=How Democrats can be progressive without being irresponsible|first1=Fred|last1=Hiatt|first2=Fred|last2=Hiatt|date=April 9, 2017|publisher=|accessdate=April 18, 2017|via=washingtonpost.com}}</ref>\n\nKhanna has co-sponsored the [[Reward Work Act of 2018]], to reform [[US labor law]] and [[US corporate law|corporate law]] by guaranteeing the right of employees in listed companies to elect one-third of the [[board of directors]].\n\n===NO PAC Caucus===\nKhanna co-founded the NO PAC Caucus<ref>{{cite web|last=Trickey |first=Erick |url=https://www.politico.com/tipsheets/politico-influence/2017/07/12/khanna-starts-pac-free-caucus-221295 |title=Khanna starts PAC-free caucus |publisher=Politico |date=July 12, 2017 |accessdate=January 19, 2018}}</ref> in Congress with two other members: Beto O'Rourke (D-Texas) and Jared Polis (D-Colo.). Three other members of Congress now refuse all contributions from political action committees: [[Phil Roe (politician)|Phil Roe]] (R-TN), [[Francis Rooney]] (R-FL), and [[John Sarbanes]] (D-MD).<ref name=\"cleanslatenow1\" /> These members do not want to fill out questionnaires and pledge positions to political action committees in exchange for contributions. Khanna and O'Rourke also introduced a bill to ban PACs from giving contributions to members of Congress.<ref name=\"politico.com1\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sfchronicle.com/opinion/openforum/article/No-PAC-Act-offers-voters-hope-to-be-heard-11056365.php|title='No PAC Act' offers voters hope to be heard|publisher=|accessdate=April 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\nKhanna has worked with constitutional scholar Bruce Ackerman and Senator [[Russ Feingold]] to propose a plan for \"Democracy Dollars\". Under the proposal, every American citizen would get $50 to spend on federal elections.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sacbee.com/opinion/california-forum/article197215689.html|title=Here\u2019s a campaign finance law that would take democracy back from the 1 percent|first=Ro Khanna And Bruce|last=Ackerman|date=July 26, 2018|publisher=|accessdate=July 26, 2018|via=Sacramento Bee}}</ref><ref>http://www.concordmonitor.com/Getting-big-money-out-of-politics-17448454</ref> Khanna has also worked across the aisle with Representative [[Mike Gallagher (American politician)|Mike Gallagher]] on reform proposals.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/opinion/2017/06/01/two-congressmen-offer-bipartisan-plan-drain-swamp/102189506/|title=Two congressmen offer a bipartisan plan to 'drain the swamp'|author=|date=|website=usatoday.com|accessdate=October 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Reforming H1B abuse===\n\nKhanna co-sponsored H.R.1303, a bipartisan companion bill to the H-1B and L-1 Visa Reform Act of 2017 designed to prevent the exploitation of foreign workers while still recognizing the contributions immigrants make to our economy. The bill would overhaul the H-1B and L-1 visa programs to protect American workers and crack down on the outsourcing of American jobs abroad.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.americanbazaaronline.com/2017/03/03/ro-khanna-introduces-bipartisan-bill-to-reduce-h-1b-l1-fraud-and-abuse/|title=Ro Khanna introduces bipartisan bill to reduce H-1B, L1 'fraud and abuse'|date=March 3, 2017|publisher=|access-date=April 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Monopolistic behavior===\n\nKhanna founded and co-chairs the [[Antitrust Caucus]] in the United States House of Representatives.<ref>{{cite web|author=Subscribe |url=https://news.vice.com/en_us/article/mb99n8/democrats-are-back-to-trust-busting |title=Democrats are back to trust busting \u2013 VICE News |publisher=News.vice.com |date=November 18, 2017 |accessdate=January 19, 2018}}</ref> He has called for a reorientation of antitrust policy to consider the impact on jobs, wages, small business, and innovation, and called for scrutiny on the Whole Foods/Amazon merger.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2017/06/ro-khanna-amazon-whole-foods/530805/|title=A Silicon Valley Congressman Takes On Amazon|first=Alexis C.|last=Madrigal|date=|website=theatlantic.com|accessdate=October 21, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibtimes.com/political-capital/amazon-whole-foods-merger-silicon-valley-lawmaker-wants-regulators-review-bezos|title=Amazon-Whole Foods Merger: Silicon Valley Lawmaker Wants Regulators To Review Bezos Deal|author=|date=June 22, 2017|website=ibtimes.com|accessdate=October 21, 2017}}</ref> \n\nIn 2018, along with Senator Bernie Sanders, Khanna proposed the BEZOS Act, which would tax firms for every dollar that employees earn in government health-care benefits or food stamps.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/09/05/bernie-sanders-introduces-the-bezos-act-slamming-amazon-low-wages.html|title=Bernie Sanders introduces the BEZOS Act, slamming Amazon's low wages|last=D'Onfro|first=Jillian|date=2018-09-05|work=CNBC|access-date=2018-09-07}}</ref> The law would also make it illegal for any large company to investigate whether or not a potential employee receives federal assistance.<ref>https://www.sanders.senate.gov/download/stop-bezos-act-2018?id=C2E88AC5-C629-4680-8F8D-9EE74F343560&download=1&inline=file</ref> Khanna's rationale for the legislation was that it would force corporations to increase salaries for workers or pay for the welfare programs their employees rely on.<ref name=\":0\" /> Economists at the [[Center on Budget and Policy Priorities]] published an analysis of the bill finding that it would hurt low-wage workers by giving corporations incentives not to hire workers that rely on federal assistance programs.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://uk.businessinsider.com/bernie-sanders-amazon-stop-bezos-bill-jeff-backfire-2018-9?r=US&IR=T|title=Joe Biden's former top economist thinks Bernie Sanders' bill attacking Amazon and Jeff Bezos 'may backfire'|work=Business Insider|access-date=2018-09-07|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbpp.org/poverty-and-inequality/sanders-khanna-bill-risks-unintended-side-effects-that-could-hurt-lower|title=Sanders-Khanna Bill Risks Unintended Side Effects That Could Hurt Lower-Income Workers and Spur Discriminatory Hiring Practices|date=2018-09-05|work=Center on Budget and Policy Priorities|access-date=2018-09-07|language=en}}</ref>\n\nKhanna wrote a letter to the inspector general of the Department of Defense requesting that he look into TransDigm Group, an aviation-parts manufacturer, and supplier of companies like Boeing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/representative-ro-khanna-calls-for-inspection-into-transdigm-2017-3|title=A battleground stock for Wall Street's short sellers is getting hammered|publisher=|accessdate=April 18, 2017}}</ref> In his letter, Khanna said TransDigm may be bypassing rules that protect U.S. taxpayers since the manufacturer conducts business with the Pentagon. He said he wants to make sure the TransDigm Group is not adding unnecessary costs to the U.S. taxpayer and is not contributing to the $54 billion increase in defense spending proposed by the Trump administration.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2017/03/22/transdigm-shares-drop-4-as-us-rep-pushes-for-probe.html|title=TransDigm shares drop more than 5% as US rep pushes for probe|first=Luqman|last=Adeniyi|date=March 22, 2017|publisher=|accessdate=April 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Foreign policy===\nOn January 18, 2018, Khanna organized a group of 33 members of the US House of Representatives to sign a letter urging Trump to re-establish military to military communications with North Korea. Khanna also called for two other steps that should be taken to alleviate tension with the DPRK. First he reintroduced a bill explicitly stating that the President of the United States should not be allowed to launch a nuclear strike without congressional approval, and Khanna also called upon Trump to send a bipartisan team to negotiate directly with the North Koreans.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thehill.com/policy/defense/369582-lawmakers-call-for-military-to-military-communications-with-north-korea |title=Lawmakers call for military-to-military communications with North Korea |publisher=TheHill |date= |accessdate=January 19, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn November 13, 2017, the House of Representatives passed a resolution condemning civilian deaths, starvation and the spread of disease in Yemen, admitting that much of the responsibility for that humanitarian crisis rests with the U.S. because of its support for a Saudi-led military intervention, and noting that the war has allowed al Qaeda, ISIL, and other groups to thrive.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/house-vote-humanitarian-crisis-yemen_us_5a0a6409e4b0b17ffcdfd18a |title=Obama, Trump And Saudi Arabia Devastated Yemen. Congress Is Acting. Slowly. &#124; HuffPost |publisher=Huffingtonpost.com |date=November 14, 2017 |accessdate=January 19, 2018}}</ref> Khanna, along with Representative [[Jim McGovern (American politician)|Jim McGovern]], co-sponsored the resolution on the House floor. The resolution passed with a bipartisan majority of 366-30.<ref>{{cite web|last=Nilsen |first=Ella |url=https://www.vox.com/world/2017/11/14/16648848/yemen-congress-trump-saudi-salman |title=America is fueling the war in Yemen. Congress is finally pushing back. |publisher=Vox |date=November 14, 2017 |accessdate=January 19, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Trickey |first=Erick |url=https://www.politico.com/story/2017/11/13/house-yemen-civil-war-authorization-244868 |title=House declares U.S. military role in Yemen's civil war unauthorized |publisher=Politico |date=November 13, 2017 |accessdate=January 19, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Keating |first=Joshua |url=http://www.slate.com/blogs/the_slatest/2017/11/14/the_u_s_has_helped_saudi_arabia_bomb_yemen_for_almost_three_years_congress.html |title=The U.S. has helped Saudi Arabia bomb Yemen for almost three years. Congress just noticed |publisher=Slate.com |date=November 14, 2017 |accessdate=January 19, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/floor-action/house/360202-house-votes-on-us-involvement-in-yemen |title=House votes on US involvement in Yemen |publisher=TheHill |date=November 13, 2017 |accessdate=January 19, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.salon.com/2017/11/14/congress-recognizes-slams-the-unauthorized-american-war-in-yemen-in-bipartisan-resolution/ |title=Congress recognizes, slams the unauthorized American war in Yemen in bipartisan resolution |publisher=Salon.com |date= |accessdate=January 19, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://theintercept.com/2017/11/14/congress-yemen-war-unauthorized/ |title=Congress Votes to Say It Hasn't Authorized War in Yemen, Yet War in Yemen Goes On |publisher=Theintercept.com |date=November 14, 2017 |accessdate=January 19, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://theweek.com/speedreads/737249/house-declares-support-saudi-arabias-yemen-war-unauthorized-use-force |title=House declares U.S. support for Saudi Arabia's Yemen war an unauthorized use of force |publisher=Theweek.com |date=November 14, 2017 |accessdate=January 19, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Loree Lewis |url=http://www.talkmedianews.com/pentagon-news-as-it-break-from-the-pentagon/2017/11/14/house-passes-resolution-spotlighting-us-engagement-in-yemeni-civil-war-calls-for-peaceful-end/ |title=House passes resolution spotlighting US engagement in Yemeni civil war, calls for peaceful end |publisher=Talkmedianews.com |date=November 14, 2017 |accessdate=January 19, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn September 27, 2017, Khanna along with Representatives [[Thomas Massie]], [[Mark Pocan]], and [[Walter B. Jones Jr.]], submitted a bipartisan bill on the floor of the House that would halt U.S. military assistance to the Saudi-led campaign in Yemen on the grounds that Congress has never approved the American role in the war. In a joint statement with Pocan, Khanna said, \"we aim to restore Congress as the constitutionally mandated branch of government that may declare war and retain oversight over it.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thenation.com/article/congress-must-end-us-military-support-for-the-horrific-saudi-bombing-of-yemen/|title=Congress Must End US Military Support for the Horrific Saudi Bombing of Yemen|first=John|last=Nichols|date=September 28, 2017|publisher=|accessdate=October 21, 2017|via=www.thenation.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2017/09/28/lawmakers-demand-u-s-withdrawal-from-saudi-led-war-in-yemen/|title=Lawmakers Demand U.S. Withdrawal From Saudi-Led War in Yemen|author=|date=|website=foreignpolicy.com|accessdate=October 21, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/sns-wp-yemen-policy-7921641a-a477-11e7-b14f-f41773cd5a14-20170928-story.html|title=Lawmakers demand U.S. withdrawal from Saudi-led war in Yemen|first=Dan De Luce, (c) 2017, Foreign|last=Policy|date=|website=chicagotribune.com|accessdate=October 21, 2017}}</ref> Khanna, Pocan, and Jones penned an op-ed for ''The New York Times'' detailing the human cost of the continued war in Yemen, saying, \"We believe that the American people, if presented with the facts of this conflict, will oppose the use of their tax dollars to bomb and starve civilians in order to further the Saudi monarchy's regional goals.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/10/10/opinion/yemen-war-unconstitutional.html|title=Opinion - Stop the Unconstitutional War in Yemen|first1=Ro|last1=Khanna|first2=Mark|last2=Pocan|first3=Walter|last3=Jones|date=October 10, 2017|publisher=|accessdate=October 21, 2017|via=www.nytimes.com}}</ref>\n\nKhanna, a supporter of a more [[non-interventionist]] foreign policy,<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/business/archive/2017/04/ro-khanna-trillion-dollar-plan/524754/|title=Ro Khanna Wants to Give Working-Class Households $1 Trillion|first=Annie|last=Lowrey|date=|website=theatlantic.com|accessdate=October 21, 2017}}</ref> wrote an op-ed for ''[[The Los Angeles Times]]'' with Senator [[Rand Paul]] on June 1, 2017 making the case against military interventions when our security is not at risk. They argued that the nation is weary of perpetual war since 2001, and that calls for regime change abroad have been a mistake.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/opinion/op-ed/la-oe-rand-khanna-foreign-policy-john-quincy-adams-20170601-story.html|title=The case for restraint in American foreign policy|author=|date=June 1, 2017|publisher=|accessdate=October 21, 2017|via=LA Times}}</ref> Khanna has been critical of the strikes on Syria.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.msnbc.com/am-joy/watch/rep-khanna-on-syria-nation-hasn-t-learned-its-lesson-917385795880|title=Rep. Khanna on Syria: \"Nation hasn't learned its lesson\"|author=|date=|website=msnbc.com|accessdate=October 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Combating international anti-Semitism===\nOn April 25, 2018, 57 members of the House of Representatives, led by Khanna, released a condemnation of Holocaust distortion in Ukraine and Poland.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://khanna.house.gov/media/press-releases/release-rep-khanna-leads-bipartisan-members-condemning-anti-semitism-europe|title=RELEASE: Rep. Khanna Leads Bipartisan Members In Condemning Anti-Semitism in Europe|date=April 25, 2018|publisher=|accessdate=July 26, 2018}}</ref><ref>http://defendinghistory.com/57-members-of-us-house-of-representatives-condemn-holocaust-distortion-in-ukraine-and-poland/94506</ref> The condemnation came in an open bipartisan letter to Deputy Secretary of State John Sullivan.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.jta.org/2018/04/25/news-opinion/congress-members-urge-a-us-stand-against-state-sponsored-holocaust-denial-in-ukraine-and-poland|title=Congress members call out Ukraine government for glorifying Nazis - Jewish Telegraphic Agency|website=www.jta.org|accessdate=July 26, 2018}}</ref> The letter read in part, \"We urge you to join us and human rights organizations in standing against anti-Semitism, xenophobia, and all forms of intolerance by calling for the Polish and Ukrainian governments to unequivocally reject Holocaust distortion and the honoring of Nazi collaborators and fully prosecute anti-Semitic crimes. We also ask that you detail what steps are being taken by the United States (U.S.) government to monitor instances of Holocaust distortion and ensure that the U.S. is not supporting or funding groups and individuals that promote or justify anti-Semitism. We believe these steps must include a firm request that these offensive laws be repealed.\"<ref>https://khanna.house.gov/sites/khanna.house.gov/files/Combat%20Anti-Semitism%20Letter.pdf</ref> California's State Assembly passed a separate resolution calling upon Congress to pressure Polish lawmakers to change this new Holocaust speech law.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://leginfo.legislature.ca.gov/faces/billTextClient.xhtml?bill_id=201720180AJR35|title=Bill Text - AJR-35 Polish law: Holocaust speech.|website=leginfo.legislature.ca.gov|accessdate=July 26, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.jweekly.com/2018/05/30/state-assembly-resolution-urges-changes-polish-holocaust-law/|title=State Assembly resolution urges changes in Polish Holocaust law \u2013 J.|date=May 30, 2018|publisher=J Weekly|accessdate=July 26, 2018}}</ref> Andrzej Pawluszek, an adviser to Polish Prime Minister Mateusz Morawiecki, called the claims in Congress's letter \"irresponsible and shocking.\"<ref>https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/congress/poland-rebukes-us-criticism-of-holocaust-law/2018/04/26/fd4141dc-4947-11e8-8082-105a446d19b8_story.html?noredirect=on</ref> The Association of Jewish Organizations and Communities of Ukraine ([[Vaad]] of Ukraine) also rebuked the letter, calling it \"anti-Ukrainian [[defamation]]\" like that used by Russian propaganda during the [[Russian military intervention in Ukraine (2014\u2013present)|war in Ukraine]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vaadua.org/news/zayava-prezidiumu-vaadu-ukrayini-u-zvyazku-z-listom-kongresmeniv-ssha-pro-situaciyu-z|title=\u0417\u0430\u044f\u0432\u0430 \u041f\u0440\u0435\u0437\u0438\u0434\u0456\u0457 \u0412\u0430\u0430\u0434\u0443 \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0438 \u0443 \u0437\u0432\u2019\u044f\u0437\u043a\u0443 \u0437 \u043b\u0438\u0441\u0442\u043e\u043c \u043a\u043e\u043d\u0433\u0440\u0435\u0441\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0456\u0432 \u0421\u0428\u0410 \u043f\u0440\u043e \u0441\u0438\u0442\u0443\u0430\u0446\u0456\u044e \u0437 \u0430\u043d\u0442\u0438\u0441\u0435\u043c\u0456\u0442\u0438\u0437\u043c\u043e\u043c \u0432 \u041f\u043e\u043b\u044c\u0449\u0456 \u0442\u0430 \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0456|date=May 10, 2018|publisher=|accessdate=July 26, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.istpravda.com.ua/articles/2018/05/10/152438/|title=\u041f\u0440\u043e \u044f\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u00ab\u0430\u043d\u0442\u0438\u0441\u0435\u043c\u0456\u0442\u0438\u0437\u043c\u00bb \u043f\u0438\u0448\u0443\u0442\u044c \u043a\u043e\u043d\u0433\u0440\u0435\u0441\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0438 \u0421\u0428\u0410? \u0417\u0430\u044f\u0432\u0430 \u0412\u0430\u0430\u0434 \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0438|publisher=istpravda.com.ua|accessdate=July 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2016 elections===\nKhanna was one of the few Representatives to endorse [[Bernie Sanders]] for [[President of the United States]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://johnhalle.com/outragesandinterludes/ro-khanna-to-justice-democrats-i-endorsed-bernie-sanders-did-he-lie/|title=Ro Khanna to Justice Democrats: \"I Endorsed Bernie Sanders.\" Did he Lie? (Update: NO!) - Outrages and Interludes|date=May 13, 2017|publisher=|accessdate=July 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Electoral history in the U.S. House of Representatives==\n\n===2004 and 2012 elections===\nKhanna ran one of the nation's first anti-Iraq war campaigns for the [[United States House of Representatives]] in the [[United States House of Representatives elections in California, 2004|2004 elections]], unsuccessfully challenging [[Tom Lantos]] in the Democratic primary in {{ushr|CA|12}}.<ref name=\"newsbank1\">{{cite news|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=SMCB&p_theme=smcb&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=10074A629BAB3A35&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|title=City Supervisor endorses Khanna|first=Justin|last=Jouvenal|date=January 17, 2004|newspaper=San Mateo County Times|accessdate=April 5, 2013}} {{subscription required|date=April 2013}}</ref> He received endorsements from prominent officials, including [[Matt Gonzalez]],<ref name=\"newsbank1\"/> and newspapers, including the ''[[San Mateo County Times]]'',<ref>{{cite news|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=SMCB&p_theme=smcb&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=1011827F96C92B3D&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|title=We can entrust America with Khanna's principles|first1=Libby|last1=Traubman|first2=Len|last2=Traubman|date=February 17, 2004|newspaper=San Mateo County Times|accessdate=April 5, 2013}} {{subscription required|date=April 2013}}</ref> but lost.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.insidebayarea.com/breaking-news/ci_22512406/rep-mike-honda-digs-against-potential-challenger-ro|title=Rep. Mike Honda digs in against potential challenger Ro Khanna|publisher=Inside Bay Area|date=February 4, 2013|accessdate=April 5, 2013}}</ref>\n\nKhanna intended to run for the House in {{ushr|CA|15}} in the [[United States House of Representatives elections in California, 2012|2012 election]], hoping to succeed Democrat [[Pete Stark]] after Stark's eventual retirement, though stating he would not challenge Stark directly.<ref name=sfgate2012/> He raised $1.2 million, receiving support from Governor Brown, [[Leaders of the United States House of Representatives|House Minority Leader]] [[Nancy Pelosi]], former [[United States Secretary of Transportation|Secretary of Transportation]] [[Norman Mineta]] Representatives [[Zoe Lofgren]] and [[Anna Eshoo]], and businessmen [[Vinod Khosla]] and [[John W. Thompson]].<ref name=sfgate2012>{{cite news|author=Carla Marinucci, Chronicle Political Writer|url=http://www.sfgate.com/politics/article/Pete-Stark-may-put-Ro-Khanna-s-rise-on-hold-2641389.php|title=Pete Stark may put Ro Khanna's rise on hold|publisher=SFGate|date=January 20, 2012|accessdate=January 24, 2013}}</ref> Khanna's fundraising total for the fourth quarter of 2011 exceeded that of all but two House candidates nationwide.<ref name=mercury>{{cite web|url=http://www.mercurynews.com/top-stories/ci_19922331|title=Silicon Valley Democrat tops in fundraising, even though he's not running yet|publisher=Mercurynews.com|accessdate=January 24, 2013}}</ref> [[Eric Swalwell]] defeated Stark in 2012.<ref>{{cite web|author=Molly Redden|url=http://www.tnr.com/blog/plank/110548/course-the-man-who-ousted-pete-stark-costume-donning-prop-loving-thirtysomething#|title=Eric Swalwell, Pete Stark's Young Vanquisher, Gets Oriented|publisher=Tnr.com|date=December 5, 2012|accessdate=January 24, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===2014 election===\n{{Election box begin no change|title=[[United States House of Representatives elections, 2014]]<ref>[http://elections.cdn.sos.ca.gov/sov/2014-general/pdf/43-congress.pdf Office of the California Secretary of State] \"United States Representative in Congress\"; retrieved January 22, 2014.</ref>}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change| |party=Democratic Party (United States)|candidate=[[Mike Honda]] (incumbent)|votes=69,561|percentage=51.8}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change| |party=Democratic Party (United States)|candidate=Ro Khanna|votes=64,847|percentage=48.2}}\n{{Election box total no change| |votes=134,408|percentage=100}}\n{{Election box turnout no change| |percentage=}}\n{{Election box hold with party link without swing| |winner=Democratic Party (United States)}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\nOn April 2, 2013, Khanna announced that he would challenge [[Mike Honda]] in {{ushr|CA|17}} in the 2014 midterm elections.<ref>{{cite web|last=Richman|first=Josh|title=Silicon Valley Congressional battle takes shape: Ro Khanna to challenge Mike Honda, using Obama campaign operatives|url=http://www.mercurynews.com/bay-area-news/ci_22916803/silicon-valley-congressional-battle-takes-shape-ro-khanna|work=San Jose Mercury News|accessdate=April 5, 2013}}</ref> Khanna assembled a campaign team composed of top members of President Obama's reelection team, including [[Jeremy Bird]], Obama's 2012 national field director, and Steve Spinner, one of Obama's top three fundraisers.<ref>{{cite web|last=Green|first=Joshua|title=Ro Khanna, Silicon Valley's Wannabe Obama|url=http://www.businessweek.com/articles/2013-04-04/ro-khanna-silicon-valleys-wannabe-obama|work=Businessweek|publisher=Bloomberg|accessdate=April 5, 2013}}</ref> Khanna was backed by executives at [[Google]], [[Facebook]], [[Yahoo]] and other tech companies,<ref>Onishi, Norimitsu (February 5, 2014) [https://www.nytimes.com/2014/02/06/us/politics/tech-industry-flexes-muscle-in-california-race.html?ref=todayspaper&_r=0 \"Tech Industry Flexes Muscle in California Race.\"] New York Times; retrieved September 2, 2014.</ref> and by the [[editorial board]]s of the ''[[San Jose Mercury News]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mercurynews.com/opinion/ci_25732079/mercury-news-editorial-ro-khanna-should-replace-mike|title=Mercury News editorial: Ro Khanna should replace Mike Honda in Congress|publisher=Mercurynews.com|date=May 3, 2014|accessdate=May 21, 2014}}</ref> the ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sfgate.com/opinion/editorials/article/Ro-Khanena-offers-upgrade-in-Congress-for-Silicon-5452296.php|title=Ro Khanna offers upgrade in Congress for Silicon Valley|publisher=SFGate|date=May 4, 2014|accessdate=May 21, 2014}}</ref> the ''[[Oakland Tribune]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.contracostatimes.com/news/ci_25746976/oakland-tribune-editorial-ro-khanna-should-replace-mike|title=Oakland Tribune editorial: Ro Khanna should replace Mike Honda in Congress|publisher=ContraCostaTimes.com|accessdate=May 21, 2014}}</ref> and the ''[[Contra Costa Times]]''.<ref>{{cite web|author=Contra Costa Times/Oakland Tribune|url=http://www.contracostatimes.com/endorsements/ci_25746930/2014-election-recommendations-contra-costa-times-editorial-board|title=June 2014 election recommendations from the Contra Costa Times/Oakland Tribune editorial board|publisher=ContraCostaTimes.com|accessdate=May 21, 2014}}</ref> Khanna earned the endorsement of [[San Jose, California|San Jose]] Mayor [[Chuck Reed]],<ref>[http://www.mercurynews.com/nation-world/ci_26350031/san-jose-mayor-chuck-reed-endorses-ro-khanna Chuck Reed endorses Ro Khanna], mercurynews.com; accessed December 1, 2014.</ref> and also won the endorsement of the Silicon Valley Chamber of Commerce.<ref>[http://www.mercurynews.com/nation-world/ci_26373773/silicon-valley-chamber-endorses-ro-khanna-over-mike Silicon Valley Chamber of Commerce endorses Ro Khanna over Mike Honda], mercurynews.com; accessed December 1, 2014.</ref>\n\nA lawsuit was filed before the Sacramento County Superior Court alleging that Khanna had recruited candidates with similar names to enter the race as Republicans to split the Republican vote three ways. On March 28, 2014, the Court disqualified one of the candidates and ruled that Khanna had no connection with the incident.<ref>{{cite web|title=Indian-American Vinesh Singh Rathore ousted from Congressional race|url=http://news.biharprabha.com/2014/03/indian-american-vinesh-singh-rathore-ousted-from-congressional-race|work=IANS|publisher=news.biharprabha.com|accessdate=March 29, 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn November 4, 2014, incumbent congressman Honda defeated Khanna 69,561 (51.8%) votes to 64,847 (48.2%). Khanna's campaign was funded by many of the technology industry's biggest names, including Yahoo chief executive Marissa Mayer, Facebook executive Sheryl Sandberg, Google Chairman Eric Schmidt, Napster founder Sean Parker, investor Marc Andreessen, and venture capitalist Steve Westly.<ref>{{cite web|last=Rucker|first=Philip|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/in-silicon-valley-tech-titans-try-to-replace-a-longtime-democratic-congressman/2014/06/02/b09cfc02-e84f-11e3-8f90-73e071f3d637_story.html|title=In Silicon Valley, tech titans try to replace a longtime Democratic congressman|publisher=The Washington Post|date=June 2, 2014|accessdate=February 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===2016 election===\n\n{{Election box begin no change|title=[[United States House of Representatives elections, 2016]]<ref>[http://vote.sos.ca.gov/returns/us-rep/district/17/ Office of the California Secretary of State] \"United States Representative in Congress\"; retrieved November 27, 2016.</ref>}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change| |party=Democratic Party (United States)|candidate=[[Mike Honda]] (incumbent)|votes=90,919|percentage=39.0}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change| |party=Democratic Party (United States)|candidate=Ro Khanna|votes=142,262|percentage=61.0}}\n{{Election box total no change| |votes=233,181|percentage=100}}\n{{Election box hold with party link without swing| |winner=Democratic Party (United States)}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n{{Election box open primary begin no change\n| title = [[California's 17th congressional district]] primary election, 2016<ref>[http://vote.sos.ca.gov/returns/us-rep/district/17 Office of the California Secretary of State] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160614185741/http://vote.sos.ca.gov/returns/us-rep/district/17 |date=June 14, 2016 }} \"United States Representative in Congress,\" (retrieved June 18, 2016)</ref>\n}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n| party = Democratic Party (United States)\n| candidate = Ro Khanna\n| votes = 52,059\n| percentage = 39.1\n}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n| party = Democratic Party (United States)\n| candidate = [[Mike Honda]] ([[incumbent]])\n| votes = 49,823\n| percentage = 37.4\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| party = Republican Party (United States)\n| candidate = Peter Kuo\n| votes = 12,224\n| percentage = 9.2\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| party = Republican Party (United States)\n| candidate = Ron Cohen\n| votes = 10,448\n| percentage = 7.8\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| party = Democratic Party (United States)\n| candidate = [[Pierluigi Oliverio|Pierluigi C. Oliverio]]\n| votes = 5,533\n| percentage = 4.2\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| party = Libertarian Party (United States)\n| candidate = Kennita Watson\n| votes = 3,125\n| percentage = 2.3\n}}\n{{Election box total no change\n| votes = 133,212\n| percentage = 100\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\nIn June 2015, Khanna announced his intention to run again for the [[U.S. House of Representatives]] in [[California's 17th congressional district]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.americanbazaaronline.com/2015/06/02/ro-khanna-launches-his-3rd-bid-to-become-a-congressman-and-unseat-the-dozer-mike-honda|title=Ro Khanna launches his 3rd bid to become a Congressman and unseat 'the dozer' Mike Honda|last=Karerat|first=Raif|date=June 2, 2015|publisher=The American Bazaar|accessdate=February 16, 2016}}</ref> He took no donations from PACs or corporations for his 2016 campaign. Khanna raised $480,500 from individuals associated with the securities and investment industry and $170,752 from individuals associated with the electronics manufacturing industry.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.opensecrets.org/news/2016/06/wall-streets-fab-five-the-house-candidates-most-dependent-on-the-finance-industry|title=Wall Street's fab five: House members, candidates most reliant on funding from finance industry|date=June 1, 2016|website=OpenSecrets Blog|language=en-US|access-date=June 15, 2016}}</ref> All these donations were subject to the $2,700 individual contributions cap. On June 7, 2016, Khanna won the primary with 52,059 (39.1%) votes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://vote.sos.ca.gov/returns/us-rep/district/17|title=U.S. House of Representatives District 17 - Districtwide Results|website=vote.sos.ca.gov|access-date=June 15, 2016|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160614185741/http://vote.sos.ca.gov/returns/us-rep/district/17|archivedate=June 14, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Honda came in second with 49,823 (37.4%) votes. The two Democrats advanced to the general election on November 8, 2016. Khanna became the Representative-elect on November 8 after defeating Honda, 84,392 (60%) to 56,787 (40%).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mercurynews.com/elections/ci_29989930/district-17-rematch-expected-between-rep-honda-and|title=Mike Honda vs. Ro Khanna: Rematch set in District 17 congressional race|website=mercurynews.com|access-date=June 15, 2016}}</ref> According to the ''East Bay Times,'' Khanna won using a campaign platform focused on \"moving the Democratic Party to a more progressive stance.\" He held his first town hall as a congressman on February 22, 2017, at [[Ohlone College]].<ref name=\"EastBayTimes_2017\">{{Citation\n | last =Geha\n | first = Joseph\n | title =Khanna says Democrats must be more \"far more bold\" at first town hall\n | newspaper = [[East Bay Times]]\n | date =February 23, 2017\n | url = http://www.eastbaytimes.com/2017/02/23/khanna-says-democrats-must-be-more-far-more-bold-at-first-town-hall/\n | access-date = February 28, 2017}}</ref> On May 10, 2017, Khanna officially joined the [[Justice Democrats]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/politics/essential/la-pol-ca-essential-politics-updates-rep-ro-khanna-joins-progressive-group-1494621068-htmlstory.html|title=California politics updates: Gov. Brown's adds cash to budget; McClintock calls for independent prosecutor for Russia investigation|work=Los Angeles Times|access-date=May 15, 2017|language=en-US|issn=0458-3035}}</ref>\n\nKhanna is a member of the [[Congressional Progressive Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|author=|url=https://cpc.grijalva.house.gov/index.cfm?sectionid=71&sectiontree=2,71|format=|publisher=Congressional Progressive Caucus|date=|accessdate=October 12, 2017|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171022024104/https://cpc.grijalva.house.gov/index.cfm?sectionid=71&sectiontree=2,71|archivedate=October 22, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> and the [[Congressional Asian Pacific American Caucus]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|author=|url=https://capac-chu.house.gov/members|format=|publisher=Congressional Asian Pacific American Caucus|date=|accessdate=17 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nKhanna resides in [[Fremont, California]], with his wife, Ritu. Ritu Khanna's father is the chairman of Mura Holdings, an investment firm, and is the chief executive of Transmaxx, an automotive transmission parts supplier, both in Solon, Ohio.<ref name=sfgate2012/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/08/30/fashion/weddings/ritu-ahuja-and-rohit-khanna.html?_r=2&referrer#modal-lightbox |title=Ritu Khanna and Rohit Khanna |publisher=New York Times2015 |date=August 15, 2015 |accessdate=February 16, 2016}}</ref> In July 2017, they had their first child, a boy named Soren.\n\nAs of 2016, Khanna was a Vice President for Strategic Initiatives at Smart Utility Systems, an energy efficiency company with an office in Santa Clara. Smart Utility Systems produces software for water conservation and for reducing electricity consumption.<ref>{{cite web|first=Josh|last=Richman|url=http://www.mercurynews.com/nation-world/ci_27387641/political-blotter-ro-khannas-new-job-mike-hondas|title=Political Blotter: Ro Khanna's new job|publisher=San Jose Mercury News|date=January 26, 2015|accessdate=February 16, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smartusys.com/company.html|title=SUS: Company: Our Management Team|publisher=Smartusys.com|accessdate=February 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite book|last=Khanna|first=Ro|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Entrepreneurial_Nation_Why_Manufacturing.html?id=QsmU6YWMCnEC|title=Entrepreneurial Nation: Why Manufacturing is Still Key to America's Future|publisher=[[McGraw Hill Professional]]|year=2012|isbn=9780071802000}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Congressional Asian Pacific American Caucus]]\n* [[List of United States Representatives from California]]\n* [[List of Asian Americans and Pacific Islands Americans in the United States Congress]]\n* [[United States House of Representatives elections in California, 2014]]\n* [[Politics of California]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://khanna.house.gov/ Congressman Ro Khanna] offici